T2	p 103 191	The Spanish employers warn that 'Trioza eritreae' threatens citrus plantations in Huelva
T3	p 192 434	CASTELLO. The Spanish citrus employers' association, the Citrus Management Committee, warns of the rapid spread along the Portuguese coast of the vector of the deadliest disease of this crop, the yellow dragon, greening or huanlongbing (HLB).
T4	p 435 1087	After the Trioza eritreae was detected for the first time in October 2021 in the Algarve, specifically in the Portuguese citrus-growing region of Aljezur, one year later this insect "It has colonized some 200 kilometers of the Portuguese Atlantic coast further south and is now less than 120 kilometers from the first plantations in Huelva, in Ayamonte," the CGC points out. With this, since it was detected in Porto in 2015, the feared psyllid has expanded without interruption along the entire coast of the neighboring country and has also colonized part of Galicia (where it was detected before, in 2014), Cantabria, Asturias and the country Basque.
